🧵 PART 1 — What does an OS thread actually do?

An OS thread is created and managed by the Operating System (Windows/Linux).

It is responsible for:

-Executing instructions
-Maintaining its own stack memory
-Context switching
-CPU scheduling

Think of OS thread as:

A worker provided by the operating system.

Each OS thread has:

(i)   Dedicated stack memory (usually ~1MB default)
(ii)  Kernel resources
(iii) Managed scheduling by OS


🟠 Old Java Model (Platform Threads)

1 Java Thread = 1 OS Thread

If you create:

new Thread(...).start();

JVM asks OS:

“Give me one real thread.”

OS creates:

-Thread control block
-Stack memory
-Scheduling slot

So every Java thread:

Consumes OS memory
Consumes kernel resources


🧵 PART 2 — What does a Virtual Thread do?

A virtual thread is managed by the JVM itself.

Instead of:

1 Java thread = 1 OS thread

We now have:

Many virtual threads → Few OS threads


What happens internally?

When virtual thread runs:

-It is mounted on an OS thread
-It executes normally

When it blocks (like I/O):

a.JVM saves its stack into heap
b.Detaches it from OS thread
c.OS thread is freed for other tasks

Later:

a.Virtual thread resumes
b.Gets mounted again

Why is this better?

Because OS threads are:

-Heavy
-Limited
-Expensive to create

Virtual threads are:

-Lightweight
-Heap-based stack
-JVM scheduled

So instead of 10,000 OS threads,
you might have:

10 OS threads
100,000 virtual threads

Huge memory savings.

🧠 Now your smart question:

“If OS has less memory, why move stack to heap? Isn't heap also memory?”

Yes — heap is also memory.

But here is the difference:

(i)OS Thread Stack Memory
(ii)Allocated in native memory
(iii)Fixed size (like 1MB per thread)
(iv)Reserved upfront
(v)Not dynamically shrinkable
(vi)Outside JVM GC control

If you create 10,000 threads:

10,000 × 1MB = 10GB memory reserved

Even if threads are idle.

-Virtual Thread Stack
-Stored in heap
-Grows dynamically
-Can shrink
-Managed by GC
-Only uses memory when needed

If 10,000 virtual threads are waiting:

-Only small stack snapshots stored
-Not full 1MB each

So:

OS stack = fixed, heavy
Virtual stack = dynamic, flexible

That’s why it’s better.

🧠 Now second smart question:

“If OS memory was a problem, why was PermGen moved to Metaspace?”

Excellent connection 👏

Let’s clarify that separately.

🔴 What Was PermGen?

In Java 8 and earlier:

PermGen was:

(i)Part of heap
(ii)Fixed size

Stored:

a.Class metadata
b.Method metadata
c.Static fields

Problem:

-Fixed size
-If too many classes loaded → OutOfMemoryError
-Hard to tune


🟢 Why Metaspace Was Introduced

In Java 8:

PermGen was removed.

Replaced with:

Metaspace.

Key difference:

-Uses native memory
-Not part of heap
-Can grow dynamically

Why move it outside heap?

Because:

-Class metadata size is unpredictable
-It should not compete with object heap

Dynamic class loading (frameworks, proxies, Spring, Hibernate) caused frequent OOM
in PermGen


🧠 Important Distinction

-Virtual thread stack moved to heap
-PermGen moved to native memory

These changes were solving different problems.

Why are they different?


Virtual Threads:

Goal → Reduce OS thread overhead
Solution → Use heap-managed stack

PermGen:

Goal → Avoid fixed-size metadata region
Solution → Use dynamic native memory

They solve separate issues.

🧠 Big Picture Summary
Feature	            Old	                New	                      Why

Java Threads	    OS threads	        Virtual threads	          Reduce OS overhead
Thread stack	    Native memory	    Heap	                  Dynamic, scalable
PermGen	            Fixed heap area	    Metaspace (native)	      Avoid OOM, flexible


🎯 Final Clean Understanding

-OS thread = heavy worker from OS
-Virtual thread = lightweight worker managed by JVM
-Virtual stack in heap is flexible and GC-managed
-PermGen moved to Metaspace to avoid fixed memory limit problems

These are separate architectural decisions

